column1: Who will win the Democratic Party nomination for the US presidential election?
column6: ['US Politics']
column11: This question was closed with the answer "Hillary Clinton" on 27 July 2016 with an end date of 26 July 2016. On 26 July 2016, Hillary Clinton become the official nominee of the Democratic party (Washington Post, NY Times) For more information on the candidates, the primary process, and the primary schedule see: Candidates, How the Presidential Primary Works, Schedule. Recommended Questions Who will win the Republican Party nomination for the US presidential election? Will the Republican candidate for president win the party's nomination on the first ballot at the party's convention in July?

column6: At this stage there isn't another serious candidate
According to the general news, 538.com, PredictIt.com, and GJP consensus.
Source considered: http://www.nytimes.com/video/us/elections/100000004525555/sanders-endorses-clinton.html

Bernie endorsed Hillary today and the FBI/DOJ have declined to indict her for the email scandals. I fully expect the Congress will throw their arms and legs around in a few more inquiries into various aspects of the email scandal but I am highly confident that nothing will come out of it.

Now that Sanders endorsed Clinton [1], I think the Clinton nomination should have a higher probability, but half percent points are not allowed. She could still die, although there's a smaller than 1% chance. Clinton's probability of becoming the next POTUS is higher too.
Mr Sanders endorses Hillary which is done in perfect timing, not too soon and just before the convention.

Bernie "endorsing Hillary, she is endorsing Bernie because they adopted an exceptionally progressive Democratic Party platform in Orlando" http://nhpr.org/post/nh-sanders-supporter-reflects-campaign-victory-sanders-ideas ---- He did it, again!
I am forecasting based on the general news reports, PredictIt.com, 538.com, and GJP consensus.
I would have this 98% Hillary, 1% Bernie and 1% Other, but there was no option for other.
Leaving this at 99% even though Clinton is the winner and email issues is no longer a problem. But anything could happen between now and July 24.

"The investigation into Hillary Clinton’s email server is over" [1], so it's pretty much written in stone now. Hillary Clinton dying or having cancer (about one percent chance) would be the only reasons she would not be the democratic presidential nominee.
Now that Hillary has won the "FBI primary," it's settled.
Increasing this from 99% to 100% due to the passage of time - I'd rate this as closer to 100% than to 99%.
Wrong call. Back up to 99% from 94%.

FBI announces no charges against Hillary. So, her nomination seems like a done deal. NY Times article on FBI decision: http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/06/us/politics/hillary-clinton-fbi-email-comey.html?_r=0 Raising my probability estimate Clinton will be nominee.
no reason to change
I would like 90% on HRC and 10% on Biden as an emergency replacement. Guess that, if it is Biden, the question will be voided.
HRC up 5% on change in perspective about the likelihood of an indictment.
Updating for passage of time.
Only if indicted before. VERY unlikely. & if she's not nominated, will be neither of the above. I'm just putting 10 for Bernie bec they insist it add up to 100%
Probably worth taking this down to 94% for the next few weeks.

Trump recently voiced something that others have probably wondered about ... that Sanders is staying in the race in the event Clinton is indicted following the FBI-DOJ investigation. Politico article: “Trump: Sanders waiting for Clinton indictment” at http://www.politico.com/story/2016/06/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-hillary-clinton-indictment-224516 I'm slightly lowering my probability estimate Clinton will be nominee.

The FBI and Justice Dept. investigation of Hillary seems to be getting to a conclusion. Media reports have noted that the FBI could recommend indictment, but the actual prosecutors in the DOJ might decide not to ... like police pushing for criminal charges but a local prosecutor feeling the case won't stick.
Agree with @Dima-K
Hedging for indictment for a few weeks.

If the Justice Dept. and FBI make a recommendation to the U.S. attorney general to indict Hillary Clinton over her emails (and Clinton Foundation aspects?), the Dem nomination process could change significantly. Recent Washington Post article: https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/attorney-general-to-back-fbi-and-justice-findings-in-clinton-email-server-probe/2016/07/01/77ce6d8e-3f78-11e6-a66f-aa6c1883b6b1_story.html As a result, I'm increasing my probability estimate somewhat that Sanders could end up the Dem nominee.

Now that Pres. Obama is going to campaign with Clinton, it seems that he probably knows that the FBI is not going to recommend indictment on the email or Clinton Foundation issues. I'm raising my probability estimate that she will be Dem nominee.
She cannot be stopped.
Barring an indictment or medical incapacity, she has already clinched.
I got to this very late in the process, and since even Bernie has now said he'll vote for HRC, I'm tempted to go for 100% Hillary. But 99% it is.
No change. Updating before resolution date & for participation purposes.
According to PredictIt.com and GJP.com
She won the most votes and there isn't going to be an indictment.

There still seems a slight chance that the FBI could come out with information so damaging to Clinton that she would have to step aside. However, I'm increasing my probability estimate that she will be Dem nominee.
Going to 100%. There isn't time for any issues to come up (most likely medical).
Updating for passage of time & participation b/f resolution of deadline date.

Rationale: Lowering HC form 100% to 99%. There is something weird going on that BS officially stays in the race although HC had enough delegates. Does BS knows something that we don't now (yet)? Apparently BS still has a plan B otherwise he could have stopped.

It is very unlikely but not impossible for the Democrats to nominate Sanders. If something disastrous happens for Clinton before the convention, giving strong reason to think she would lose to Trump, and polls show Sanders doing much better against Trump, Super delegates COULD switch.
(no change) The wikileaks plan to release something that may or may not hurt HRC is interesting:
I think she has it, but still a chance she could face charges over the emails.
Email scandal seems to be blowing over. Still can't call it 100%, though.

The FBI's investigation of Hillary Clinton is still underway. There seems to still be a chance that the FBI's findings could derail her candidacy. CNN report: http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/10/politics/clinton-server-drone-fbi/ Yet, I am raising my probability estimate that Clinton will be Dem nominee.
Clinton is now the presumptive nominee after wining California, so now the Democrats are uniting behind her.
update
1% (more like 1/200) = possible health issue w/Bill or Hillary or legal bombshell.
Updating: violated my own best principles by going to 100% for HRC a moment ago. 1% covers a multitude of possibilities, from new or escalated scandals to serious health issues.
Superdelegates won't break for Bernie, and that's his only hope now.
Prediction after California primary. Things are getting obvious now. Except, of course, some last minute unforeseen events.

Despite Hillary having more delegates (pledged and super) and the popular vote among Dems, I am hedging a little bit because of the uncertainty around the FBI investigation. I can't imagine the FBI or the DOJ pulling a rabbit out of the hat for the presumptive Dem nominee, especially one the president has already endorsed, but this is the highly unlikely event I am hedging against.

Having been properly chastened by @Shiva-Diva and @Enthu - and having checked with the betting market - I'm hedging just a bit. Interestingly, the market currently thinks (pardon the metaphor) that Joe Biden is more likely to place at the top of the ticket than Bernie is[1], which is not a ringing endorsement for the rationally of the market! But, hey, anything could happen.
Moving HRC up to 99%.
She's won a majority of the pledged delegates, and has the super delegates too.
She locked it up. Why is O'Malley even still on here? Was he honestly still running?
I'm all in. What could possibly go wrong?
Up 5% for HRC. No news from FBI. Still think the following related to servergate:
It's just not going to happen for Bernie, even if Clinton was formally charged by the DOJ. Her email scandal is no more damaging than the Trump University case is to The Don. This is a done deal.

http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-36466228. I note these are being kept open long past the winning point on the basis that they may die or something else from winning to award. Trust the president one will be on election night and not on actual swearing in.
At this point, unless she were indicted for the email situation, Hillary Clinton is going to win the nomination.
mathematically impossible for Sanders to get majority & so-called super delegates will tilt towards Clinton.
Clinton is favored to win California in 2 days, and win the majority of the votes for the nomination.
Senator Bob Corker the Senate Foreign Relations Chair on ABC "This Week" with George Stephanopoulos said Trump foreign policy "is reflective of a degree of Realism".
Hillary has more votes and does have some people that support her. Bernie has energy but he lost the early states because his name recognition did not get there early.
There is still time for a change in the ballots, although the media seems to have already settled this one.

If not last Thanksgiving; possibly this Thanksgiving: "But the most likely scenario is that Vice President Joe Biden—who has said that he regrets “every day” his decision not to run—enters the race." http://www.zerohedge.com/news/2016-06-01/sorry-hillary-former-clinton-advisor-thinks-biden-may-be-democratic-presidential-nom
Clinton is still in the lead with the super delegates.
98% HRC, 1% Bernie, 1% - 0.5% Joe Biden.
Seems a lot could still go wrong for HRC.
Clinton supporters are saying that she should stay in the race even if charged by the Department of Justice. The chances of an upsets just got cut in half.
Clinton is still in the lead with the super delegates.

News items today includes reports that FBI Director Comey will recommend to the US AG that Hillary Clinton be indicted for certain charges involving the Clinton Foundation. The original report is said to be by an established Huffington Post writer, and then the article was taken down. Normally I wouldn't give much credence to the Breitbart news site due to its partisan nature, but this story seems to have some validity: http://www.breitbart.com/big-government/2016/05/30/exclusive-huffington-post-writer-editors-deleted-my-article-on-hillarys-imminent-indictment-disabled-me-from-writing/ . Its also being posted elsewhere. As a result, I'm slightly increasing my probability estimate Sanders would win Dem nomination.
I carry on with a 100% here as numerically this is a done deal! Though I think, it is after Ms H's crowning that the problems will blow out of proportion!
Down 7% HRC. May be moving down considerably as reliable, non hearsay events are publically disclosed.
Based on delegate count. It is impossible for Bernie to turn it around from here.

Passage of time & participation.

Bernie actually has a slight chance of out lasting Hilary , if the FBI report comes out and it's damaging to Clintons image , what's left of it. She may drop out ! I am hoping for a trump vs sanders debate.

Giving Bernie a slight chance on account of Hill's email troubles and him being competitive in CA
The only thing that could save him is the DOJ prosecuting Clinton.

A month ago, Democrats were sitting pretty while Republicans squabbled. But things look different now. Democrats are scrambling, and Bernie Sanders is not only calling Hillary Clinton arrogant, he's all fired up to debate Donald Trump. On the GOP side, Trump has the delegates to clinch the Republican nomination, and his critics are all mellow now.

If charges are filed the DNC will certainly push Biden over Sanders, but this could easily fall flat on it's face (imagine the reaction from Sanders' supporters).

So I could see us all swing 100% Sanders before November. She is like a bank robber hiding at the Hole in the Wall with the Pinkertons moving in. :)

superdelegates....

HC quite likely to reach majority with only pledged delegates, although I see a chance of BS getting more support due to attacks on HC by DT, I don't see this influencing the eventual outcome.

Delegate count (http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2016/president/democratic_delegate_count.html): Hillary 2,240 (1,716 non-super, 524 super) and Bernie 1,473 (1,433 non-super, 40 super). The winner needs 2,382 delegates. There are around 1,064 delegates left up for grab, out of which HIllary needs 142 and Sanders needs 909 to secure the nomination. I am adjusting the odds higher to reflect a near-certain chance of victory for HIllary. I am still leaving 4% odds of her losing to Bernie to reflect the risk of something bad coming from the email scandal.

Even though Sanders appears to be the stronger Dem candidate vs. Trump, the Dem power structure and many Dem voters are obviously supporting Hillary, resulting in her solid position currently in terms of numbers of delegates. As was discussed on CNN yesterday, many voters want a "change agent" and quite a number of Sanders supporters actually could pivot to Trump.

If the race between Clinton and Trump starts to narrow further, and Dems realize Trump could actually win, Sanders' candidacy may look more attractive to Dem delegates and super-delegates. NBC News article: http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/who-s-more-likely-beat-donald-trump-hillary-clinton-or-n570766 I'm slightly raising my probability estimate that Sanders could end up as Dem nominee.

Down 5% HRC. Just to be clear I am at 0% that HRC will be indicted. The FBI and Justice almost certainly have to telegraph some results of the investigation before the D convention. I expect only that it will recommend different procedures and a mild rebuke for the collective judgement. OTOH even if it is only a "she said, she said" situation regarding various aides and what they might have told the FBI, it is conceivable that the results may force HRC to withdraw.
Hillary Clinton now has an unbeatable lead, Bernie can't close the gap now.
Clinton will get the majority of delegates before the convention this summer.

As Trump starts to ramp up his attacks on Hillary and Bill Clinton, her vulnerabilities as a candidate may emerge more significantly. Would this change the minds of Dem delegates and super-delegates, and Dem voters about Sanders being a better choice? Probably unlikely, but seems possible. I'm slightly increasing my probability estimate that Sanders could win in a contested convention as the Trump attacks on the Clintons increase.

The betting market is currently 97/3 in favor of HRC[1]. It's more bullish on HRC than the GJ consensus[2] but less so than my own forecast. So what gives?

I update my prediction from 48% to 51% (actually 50.2) due to the possibility of a contested convention (CC) by 2.2 points due to the following facts regarding new information about primary: -West Virginia upcoming primary is open also to residents who are not registered with another party (rules that have helped Sanders run up the score in other states) -According to PPP, Clinton holds only a slim lead among Democrats -Sanders is winning 56 percent of the independent vote -Clinton received anger from many residents from a recent comment concerning coal miners when she promised to “put coal miners out of work” -Regression toward the mean: last primary with "Clintons" faired stronger the first time. -West Virginia is rural and white, and has some of the lowest incomes in the country, which benefits Sanders. -5 upcoming primaries are OPEN or MIXED, which allows for Sanders to obtain advantage -Montana (OPEN voting), is 77% white, and 70% above 18yo -Puerto Rico (OPEN voting), has 67 delegates and superdelegates, 53% population in the age of 18-50, 77% are white; they want good medical care, PR is experiencing a major financial problems; 4 out of 7 DNC superdelegates have not endorsed a candidate; -Virgin Islands has 3 superdelegates, and no endorsed candidates; -New Jersey is MIXED and has 167 delegates, and 3 out of 8 democratic superdelegates have not endorsed a candidate. -Due to different campaign strategy, Sanders has gained favor from non-white voters from 9 to 27% (Feb 2016); This may benefit him in -Virgin islands (OPEN) which is predominantly non-white and have 12 delegates. giving each an arbitrary, conservative .1 point, I see 2.2 points increase.
Giving Bernie 5% based on the possibility that the email scandal turns nasty, but otherwise, it's Hillary all the way.

If the investigation of Clinton's email system takes certain turns, Sanders would have new momentum. Associated Press on Washington Post May 4: "US Judge: Clinton may be ordered to testify in records case" at https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/us-judge-clinton-may-be-ordered-to-testify-in-records-case/2016/05/04/fc5e791a-125d-11e6-a9b5-bf703a5a7191_story.html So, increasing my probability estimate for Sanders slightly.

Sanders closely won Indiana today, but Clinton is still far ahead in delegates.

I guess I can't put Hillary above 98% if I still have the chances of her being indicted at 2% (though even that is overly high, really; it's more like 1.5%). Aside from that, I don't see how Sanders can win at this point.
10 days later, I still find it impossible for Sanders to win.

Based upon the remaining primaries, ran models hundreds of thousands of iterations assuming (conservatively) that Clinton would continue to average about 50% (as the polls suggest). in 77.5% of those, Clinton gained enough delegates to clinch the nomination. If Clinton fails to clinch the nomination outright, Sanders still has a chance.

Sanders is losing momentum, but continues to fight on!

Even if it were tied for pledged delegates, she would win in by a huge margin with Super-delegates. I don't think a scandal is going to come out - Hillary is very, very vetted. Nevada showed a disturbing trend for the Democratic party in general, and for Bernie's chances in particular. The numbers aren't there. As in, people aren't voting, numbers are WAY down compared to 2008. Some of that is due to the fact that the DNC seems to have utterly failed to properly train volunteers, and have made voting as difficult as possible. The caucus system in particular is just rife with stories of people leaving because of confusion, ridiculously long lines, and misinformation; volunteers doing illegal things (i.e. Iowa not recounting all the Hillary votes to see if anyone had left, Nevada letting people vote with registering, both caught on video), locations that were difficult to locate, and too few people on the ground with little to no training. This favors a particular candidate, whether it is intentional or not. And it most certainly favors Hillary in the primary (and, if I may say so, the Republicans in the general - I think if Hillary is nominated the DNC may find that they could lose everything due to independents and half of their voter base's apathy or outright loathing for Hillary). But Bernie's widespread support among younger voters isn't translating into getting them out to vote. And despite the ground that he is making up among minorities (Hispanic community in particular), it may not be enough quantity or fast enough. The African-American community in particular showed in Nevada that they are still serving as Clinton's firewall, overwhelmingly voting for her, almost as overwhelmingly as they voted for Obama in 2008. And unfortunately Super Tuesday is practically designed to destroy Bernie's momentum - overwhelmingly Hillary-loving states with large black populations. If he can't get out his support (and he has plenty, basically neck and neck with Hillary at this point), and right now the numbers show he simply isn't getting people to vote the same way Obama did, then he's probably doomed. I still think he has a decent chance, as literally every day that passes he moves a little up and she moves a little down in terms of the polls - but in the caucuses and primaries its simply not translating to the tangible numbers needed and the narrative is probably not going to be pretty after Super Tuesday, despite the fact that there will still be tons of voting to be done people may simply go back to assuming that the Clinton coronation that this race was always meant to be is moving forward as intended and not bother voting.

Historically, the candidate with the backing of the political establishment of their party has the best chance of winning the nomination. There are many factors that contribute to Hillary having a better chance at winning the nomination for president. First, Hillary has the backing of the democratic party's establishment, Wallstreet, many superpacs, news sources and almost any other source of wealth that is affiliated with the democrats. Additionally, Hillary Clinton has already locked up half the Democratic superdelegates in Nevada and South Carolina before the first votes are cast in either state. The former secretary of State has won public support from half of South Carolina’s six superdelegates and three of Nevada’s eight superdelegates. Bernie Sanders has secured only one, a Democratic national committeewoman from Nevada. The superdelegates are made up of Democratic lawmakers and party leaders who can cast a vote for the party’s nominee during the Democratic National Convention. They have the freedom to back whoever they want, and are not bound by the results in their states. Currently, according to recent polls, Hillary Clinton has a 61% to 34% chance of winning the South Carolina primary, mostly because she has a large amount of support from African Americans in this area. In Nevada, however, the two candidates are basically at a tie of 50% each. Moving forward, it is somewhat likely that Bernie Sanders will gain more support in Nevada because they were hit the hardest from the financial crisis of 2008 and Bernie Sanders campaign has been centered around breaking up the big banks. Some things that could change my prediction in the foreseeable future would be the results of the SC and NV elections. According to MSNBC, Bernie Sanders has employed over 240 staffers to work on his ground game, and about 80& of them are focusing on predominantly African American areas. If Bernie can effectively use his ground game to persuade blacks to vote for him, and somehow pull a upset victory in South Carolina, the chances of Hillary winning the national election will definitely drop. However, despite Bernie gaining momentum, it is still a long shot that he can pull an upset in South Carolina. Other factors that could play a role in Hillary winning the election are what happens if she is indicted for her email controversy, but it is unlikely that that will happen. Nationally, Hillary has a lead over Bernie of 49 to 33%. There are still a good amount of undecided democratic voters in the country, and how the next couple of debates and primary's turnout could have a major impact on each candidates chances of winning the democratic primary. However, in 2008, we expected Hillary to win SC but she lost in an upset to president Obama, so an upset by Bernie in this state is not out of the question, If it does occurr, his chances of winning the democratic nomination will dramatically increase. nevertheless, since Hillary has all the cards stacked in her favor, I predict that she has a 57% chance of winning while Bernie has a 43% chance of winning the democratic primary.

Polity: Bernie Sanders has two shots to make a statement and prove he can win. If he doesn't show that in Iowa and/or New Hampshire, his campaign will lose its momentum in the primaries in the southern states where Hillary Clinton's supporters are the clear majority. Policies: Sanders is the heart of the Democratic Party, Clinton its mind. Both are credible choices for a party (although "heart" candidates tend to do worse in general elections, both in America and abroad). Politics: Hillary Clinton has the clear edge in most relevant attributes: She is more electable, better funded and the better debater. The only category in which she does not crush Bernie Sanders is the ability to excite her party. However, she is still very well liked among Democrats and presents them with the opportunity to make the first woman president. Bottom line: Hillary Clinton remains the clear favorite. Bernie Sanders needs a lot of "if"s to make his bid a successful one. Martin O'Malley's campaign never gathered any momentum and is de facto dead.
